4) Lets take out our instruments

Lets look back at the Oregon Health Plan (OHP) example we reviewed in class. To refresh your memory, this was a lottery conducted in 2008 in Oregon, targeted at low-income adults. In order to participate, you had to enroll in a waitlist, and if you won the lottery, you were eligible to enroll in Medicaid.

This is the (abreviated) data we will be using:

oregon <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/website_github/master/exampleSite/content/files/data/oregonhie_simplified2.csv")

# We will replace missing variables in two variables with 0s
oregon <- oregon %>% mutate(applied_app = ifelse(is.na(applied_app),0,applied_app),
                            approved_app = ifelse(is.na(approved_app),0,approved_app))

The data contains a selected sample of two datasets combined: Variables that end in _list are from the individuals that applied to the lottery. Variables ending in _12m are from a survey sent out to a representative subsample 12 months later. All the observations contained in this dataset were selected for the 12-month survey and actually returned it. (Note: The original survey was sent to over 58,000 individuals, and only nearly 24,000 returned it).

Heres a list of important variables that you need to identify:

Variable Description
person_id ID for the applicant
household_id ID for the household.
treatment Whether the person was selected in the lottery or not.
applied_app Submitted an application for the OHP.
approved_app Application for the OHP was approved. This variable identifies the individuals that actually enrolled in the Medicaid expansion.
employ_12m Whether an individual is employed 12 months later.

1) Inspect your data! How many people were selected for the lottery? What percentage of them actually enrolled in Medicaid?


2) Interpret the following results. What does the coefficient on treatment represent? Would you say this is a causal effect? Why or why not?


3) If we want to obtain the effect of having health insurance on employment, would the previous analysis be useful? Why or why not? What is the estimand we are obtaining from the previous regression?


4) Using the information in the dataset and an Instrumental Variable approach (hint: use the iv_robust() function from the estimatr package), estimate the effect of having health insurance on employment. Interpret your results. What is the estimand you are estimating in this case?


5) In terms of external validity, for what population is the effect we just estimated generalizable to?
